"{\"uid\": \"si.com-high-school-minnesota-athletes-from-minnesota-competing-in-the-2024-paris-summer-olympics-01j3n4wprrn3\", \"text\": \"The 2024 Paris Summer Olympics are underway as top athletes from around the globe arrive in France for a chance at Olympic glory.  Twelve athletes fromMinnesotawill compete in the Olympics, and eight of them will represent Team USA while four will compete as nationals for other countries. One athlete from Minnesota, Shane Wiskus, is an Olympic alternate.  For many of these athletes, competing inMinnesotahigh school sportswas a part of their journey to the 2024 Paris Olympics.  Here are the athletes from Minnesota competing in the 2024 Paris Summer Olympics.  Dakotah Lindwurm \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 St. Francis \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Track and Field  Lindwurm will represent Team USA and Minnesota in the women's marathon. TheSt. Francis High Schoolalumni finished third in the trials with a time of two hours, 25 minutes and 31 seconds.\\u00c2  The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s marathon is on August 11 at 1 a.m. CT.  Payton Otterdahl \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Rosemount \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Track and Field  Rosemount High Schoolalumni Payton Otterdahl qualified for the 2024 Olympics in Paris in shot put with a throw of 73 feet, half-an-inch at the US Olympic Trials in Eugene, Oregon.  Otterdahl won the 2014MSHSLClass 2A shot put and discus state championship for RosemountHigh School.In 2013, his junior season, Otterdahl finished second in the shot put and third in the discus in the state championship meet.  The men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s shot put first round will take place on August 2 at 1:10 p.m. The final is on August 3 at 12:35 p.m.  Suni Lee \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 St. Paul \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Artistic Gymnastics  The St. Paul native will have a chance to defend her 2020 Tokyo Olympics all-around gold medal. She finished first in the uneven bars at the 2024 U.S. Olympic Team Trials in Minneapolis.  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s artistic gymnastics begin on July 28.  Lara Dallman-Weiss \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Shoreview \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Sailing  Dallman-Weiss is a Shoreview native who will compete in the mixed dinghy-470. She grew up sailing with the Inland Lakes Yachting Association and on White Bear Lake.  She attended Eckerd College in Florida. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been a member of the White Bear Yacht Club.\\u00c2  She was an Olympian in 2021 and finished 12th. The mixed dinghy sailing competition will begin on August 2.  Regan Smith \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Lakeville \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Swimming  Smith will compete in the 100-meter backstroke, 200-meter backstroke and 200-meter butterfly. Smith swam for Apple Valley\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Riptide Swim Club. Smith attended Stanford University. She left before graduating to train under Bob Bowman, the former trainer of Michael Phelps.  The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100-meter backstroke heats begin on July 29. The 200-meter backstroke heats begin on August 1. The 200-meter butterfly heats begin on July 31.  Jordan Thompson \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Edina \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Volleyball  Thompson was born in Edina and competed forEdina High School.She played club volleyball for Club 43 and then Northern Lights during high school. Thompson went on to play at the University of Cincinnati. She won a gold medal in the 2020 Tokyo Olympics with Team USA.\\u00c2  Team USA begins competition on July 29 against China at 10 a.m.  Alise Willoughby \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 St. Cloud \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 BMX\\u00c2  Willoughby is from St. Cloud and competing in her fourth Olympics. She took the silver medal in the 2016 Rio Olympics. She won her third BMX racing world title in May.\\u00c2  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s BMX racing begins on August 1.  Matthew Wilkinson \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Minnetonka \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Track and Field  Wilkinson, who went toMinnetonka High School, qualified in the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 3,000-meter steeplechase via the world rankings. Wilkinson ran an 8:23 at the Team USA Olympic Trials in Eugene, Oregon to finish second, but it was his time of 8:16.59 earlier this season that earned him a trip to Paris.  The first round of the 3,000-meter steeplechase begins on August 5 at 12:04 p.m.  Shane Wiskus \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Spring Park \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Men's Artistic Gymnastics  Wiskus is an alternate for the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s artistic gymnastic team.  Alasan Ann \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Maple Grove \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Taekwondo (The Gambia)  Ann graduated fromMaple Grove High Schoolin 2019. He is the first athlete to represent The Gambia in the Olympics in taekwondo. He was born in the United States, but his father is from The Gambia. He attended the World Taekwondo Academy in Maple Grove.  Taekwondo begins on August 7.  Joseph Fahnbulleh \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Hopkins \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Track and Field (Liberia)  Fahnbulleh was born in Hopkins and attendedHopkins High School. He won the 2018 and 2019 MSHSL Class 2A 200-meters championship, and he finished fourth in the triple jump in 2019.  He attended the University of Florida. He was the Liberian flag holder in the 2020 Tokyo Olympic games.  He is competing in the 200-meter dash and the 4x100-meter relay. The 200-meter dash begins on August 5, and the 4x100-meter relay begins on August 8.  Nuni Omot \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Mahtomedi \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Basketball (South Sudan)  Omot moved to Minnesota as a child, and he played basketball atMahtomedi High Schoolin his senior season. He played for Concordia University, St. Paul before transferring and eventually landing at Baylor University.\\u00c2  South Sudan opens against Puerto Rico on July 28 at 4 a.m.  Akeem Sirleaf \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 North St. Paul \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 Track and Field (Liberia)  Sirleaf graduated fromNorth St. Paul High School. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be on the Liberian 4x100-meter relay with Fahnbulleh.  To get live updates on your phone - as well as follow your favorite teams and top games - you can download the SBLive Sports app:\\u00c2Download iPhone App|\\u00c2\\u00a0Download Android App  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Jack Butler | butler@scorebooklive.com |\\u00c2@Butler917\\u00c2\\u00a0on X  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Jack Butler is the Regional Editor of the Midwest for SBLive/High School on SI. Jack has covered high school sports in Oregon, Arizona and Minnesota.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"